manual_description: ‘Japan's Megacity', Tokyo is one of the world's most exciting cities, with a culture that's rich in tradition and contemporary creativity. The city is cosmopolitan and sprawling, with ancient temples, modern skyscrapers, and traditional gardens, all surrounded by a beautiful natural setting less than an hour away.
place_description: Tokyo, Japan's busy capital, mixes the ultramodern and the traditional, from neon-lit skyscrapers to historic temples. The opulent Meiji Shinto Shrine is known for its towering gate and surrounding woods. The Imperial Palace sits amid large public gardens. The city's many museums offer exhibits ranging from classical art (in the Tokyo National Museum) to a reconstructed kabuki theater (in the Edo-Tokyo Museum).

TouristAttractions.description: World's tallest freestanding broadcasting tower with an observation deck boasting 360-degree views.
TouristAttractions.name: Tokyo Skytree
TouristAttractions.address: 1 Chome-1-2 Oshiage, Sumida City, Tokyo 131-0045, Japan

TouristAttractions.description: Surrounded by forest, this venerable Shinto shrine features a seasonal iris garden.
TouristAttractions.name: Meiji Jingu

TouristAttractions.description: Cool area known for street art, trendy youth fashion, vintage & cosplay shops & casual street fare.
TouristAttractions.name: Harajuku

TouristAttractions.description: Completed in 645, this temple, Tokyo's oldest, was built to honor Kannon, the goddess of mercy.
TouristAttractions.name: Sensō-ji
TouristAttractions.address: 2 Chome-3-1 Asakusa, Taito City, Tokyo 111-0032, Japan

TouristAttractions.description: Reminiscent of the Eiffel Tower, this landmark features observation areas & other attractions.
TouristAttractions.name: Tokyo Tower
TouristAttractions.address: 4 Chome-2-8 Shibakoen, Minato City, Tokyo 105-0011, Japan

TouristAttractions.description: Stately museum complex devoted to the art & antiquities of Japan, as well as other Asian countries.
TouristAttractions.name: Tokyo National Museum

TouristAttractions.description: Shibuya Scramble Crossing, located outside Shibuya station in Tokyo, is a must-see experience for visitors. It's the world's busiest pedestrian crossing, with over one million people crossing it daily. The surrounding shopping centers offer various lookout points to observe the madness below, and the new Shibuya Sky outdoor viewing deck provides a stunning view from 229 meters above street level. For great photos, shooting from above at night captures the neon lights and bustling activity.
TouristAttractions.name: Shibuya Scramble Crossing

TouristAttractions.description: Whimsical museum dedicated to the famed animation studio with a play area, theater & rooftop garden.
TouristAttractions.name: Ghibli Museum

TouristAttractions.description: Large, public city park with lakes, fountains & forested areas with mature trees.
TouristAttractions.name: Yoyogi Park

TouristAttractions.description: Large landscaped gardens in the grounds of a palace first built in 1888, with some Edo castle ruins.
TouristAttractions.name: Imperial Palace East National Gardens

TouristAttractions.description: This former estate is now a 144-acre park with diverse garden areas, grassy expanses & a greenhouse.
TouristAttractions.name: Shinjuku Gyoen National Garden

TouristAttractions.description: teamLab Planets is a unique digital art museum that offers an immersive and interactive experience for visitors. Opened in 2018, it was initially intended to be temporary but has since become a popular attraction. The museum features surreal and interactive digital worlds influenced by factors such as time of day, number of visitors, and even the time of year. Visitors can walk through various rooms filled with colorful digital animations and ambient sounds, becoming part of the art themselves.
TouristAttractions.name: teamLab Planets
TouristAttractions.address: 6 Chome-1-16 Toyosu, Koto City, Tokyo 135-0061, Japan

TouristAttractions.description: This site with scenic gardens & tours of the grounds is the main residence of the emperor of Japan.
TouristAttractions.name: Imperial Palace

TouristAttractions.description: Sprawling wholesale fish market with an array of seafood & viewing areas for a popular tuna auction.
TouristAttractions.name: Tsukiji Outer Market
TouristAttractions.address: 及び６丁目一部, 4 Chome Tsukiji, Chuo City, Tokyo 104-0045, Japan

TouristAttractions.description: Festive, popular city district famed for its narrow, winding alleys & numerous snug taverns.
TouristAttractions.name: Shinjuku Golden-Gai
TouristAttractions.address: 1 Chome-1-6 Kabukicho, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0021, Japan

TouristAttractions.description: Part of the Disney resort, this large park has 7 themed ports of call with rides, shows & dining.
TouristAttractions.name: Tokyo DisneySea

TouristAttractions.description: One of the city’s top shopping districts, Ginza is packed with upmarket boutiques and ritzy cocktail and sushi bars. Fine jewelry is sold in the 1930s Wako Honkan department store, while ultramodern Ginza Place specializes in high-tech electronics. On weekends, main drag Chuo Dori becomes a stylish pedestrian promenade. Traditional Japanese dance and drama is staged at the landmark Kabuki-za theater.
TouristAttractions.name: Ginza

TouristAttractions.description: Popular city park featuring ample walking paths, a lake with boat rentals, a zoo & several museums.
TouristAttractions.name: Ueno Park

TouristAttractions.description: Entertainment district on an artificial island featuring museums, a Ferris wheel & more.
TouristAttractions.name: Odaiba

TouristAttractions.description: Akihabara is a buzzing shopping hub famed for its electronics retailers, ranging from tiny stalls to vast department stores like Yodobashi Multimedia Akiba. Venues specializing in manga, anime, and video games include Tokyo Anime Center, for exhibits and souvenirs, and Radio Kaikan with 10 floors of toys, trading cards, and collectibles. Staff dressed as maids or butlers serve tea and desserts at nearby maid cafes.
TouristAttractions.name: Akihabara Electric Town

TouristRestaurants.description: Sézanne is a trendy restaurant in Tokyo that quickly earned its first Michelin star after opening in 2021 and later gained a second star. The executive chef, Daniel Calvert, brings a blend of Parisian elegance and an open-minded approach to French cuisine from his experience at Per Se in New York. The seasonal menu offers precise and technically impressive dishes like Riesling-poached foie gras with apricot and verbena sauce.
TouristRestaurants.name: SÉZANNE
TouristRestaurants.address: 1 Chome-11-1 Marunouchi, Chiyoda City, Tokyo 100-6277, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Ete is a highly exclusive dining spot in Tokyo, known for its speakeasy-style entrance and exquisite culinary creations. The chef, Shoji, gained fame as Asia's Best Pastry Chef in 2020 for her couture-inspired cakes that resemble edible artworks based on designs by Chanel and Louis Vuitton. The menu features equally impressive savory dishes such as delicate tilefish in clam broth and tender abalone over deep-fried bamboo shoots.
TouristRestaurants.name: été
TouristRestaurants.address: 代々木上原羽田ビル, 3 Chome-23-1 Nishihara, Shibuya City, Tokyo 151-0066, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Tempura Motoyoshi, situated in Tokyo, is renowned for its exceptional deep-fried dishes. Chef Motoyoshi's expertise shines through in the creation of light and crispy delicacies that highlight the freshness of handpicked vegetables from Tsukiji market. The intimate dining setting allows guests to witness the chef's precise technique as he skillfully fries each dish to perfection.
TouristRestaurants.name: Tempura Motoyoshi
TouristRestaurants.address: Granbell Ebisu IV, 3階, 2 Chome-8-11 Ebisunishi, Shibuya City, Tokyo 150-0021, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Sowado, the younger sibling of the well-known izakaya Sakai Shokai, offers a delightful blend of a laid-back pub and a refined Japanese dining experience. As you enter through the sliding-metal-door, you'll find a cozy bar serving an assortment of sake, wine, and spirits where guests can enjoy drinks while waiting for a table or after their meal.
TouristRestaurants.name: Sowado
TouristRestaurants.address: 1 Chome-12-15 Hiroo, Shibuya City, Tokyo 150-0012, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Tsukemen dipping noodles with a choice of sauces, served at the counter of this busy ramen shop.
TouristRestaurants.name: Fūunji
TouristRestaurants.address: 北斗第一ビル １F, 2 Chome-14-3 Yoyogi, Shibuya City, Tokyo 151-0053, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Sukiyabashi Jiro Roppongi Hills Restaurant is a legendary sushi bar in Tokyo, run by master chef Jiro Ono since the late 1960s. It's considered one of the best places to experience traditional sushi and has gained worldwide fame. While it's notoriously difficult to secure a reservation at the original Sukiyabashi Jiro, located in Tsukiji fish market, there's a more accessible option at Sukiyabashi Jiro Roppongi.
TouristRestaurants.name: Sukiyabashi Jiro Roppongi Hills Restaurant
TouristRestaurants.address: Japan, 〒106-0032 Tokyo, Minato City, Roppongi, 6 Chome−12−2, 六本木けやき坂通り 3F

TouristRestaurants.description: Tenoshima is a modern Japanese restaurant in Tokyo that offers a unique take on high-end kaiseki cuisine. Chef Hayashi Ryohei showcases his creativity through a nine-course tasting menu that changes every two weeks, featuring locally sourced seasonal produce from farmers and fishermen across Japan. The restaurant also offers takeout items such as assorted sushi boxes, pressed sushi, roast beef, and duck meat simmered in oil.
TouristRestaurants.name: Tenoshima
TouristRestaurants.address: 南青山 1-55ビル 2階, 1 Chome-3-21 Minamiaoyama, Minato City, Tokyo 107-0062, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Compact venue for crispy tempura & house-made udon noodles with a range of accompaniments.
TouristRestaurants.name: Udon Shin
TouristRestaurants.address: 相馬ビル １F, 2 Chome-20-16 Yoyogi, Shibuya City, Tokyo 151-0053, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: GUCCI OSTERIA Tokyo is a chic Italian restaurant located on the fourth floor of Gucci's Namiki flagship store in Ginza. The restaurant, a collaboration with renowned chef Massimo Bottura, offers a unique blend of Italian and Japanese culinary traditions. Led by executive chef Antonio Iacoviello, the menu features original dishes that evolve with the seasons, incorporating ingredients from various prefectures in Japan and Italy.
TouristRestaurants.name: Gucci Osteria da Massimo Bottura
TouristRestaurants.address: 6 Chome-6-12 Ginza, 中央区 Chuo City, Tokyo 104-0061, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Genteel hotel lounge with a serene ambiance offering breakfast, afternoon tea & high tea.
TouristRestaurants.name: The Lobby Lounge
TouristRestaurants.address: The Tokyo Station Hotel, 1 Chome-9-1 Marunouchi, Chiyoda City, Tokyo 100-0005, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Ningyocho Imahan, a historic establishment with over 120 years of experience, is both a butcher and a shop offering the freshest cuts. With locations in Tokyo and Yokohama, the Nihonbashi branch comes highly recommended. Renowned for its legendary sukiyaki, the tender meat melts in your mouth as it's cooked tableside by waitresses in a rich sukiyaki broth.
TouristRestaurants.name: Ningyocho Imahan
TouristRestaurants.address: 2 Chome-9-12 Nihonbashiningyocho, Chuo City, Tokyo 103-0013, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: The Pizza Bar On 38th, located inside the Mandarin Oriental Hotel in Nihonbashi, has gained recognition for its unique approach to pizza-making. With a focus on creating an intimate and personal dining experience akin to sushi or kaiseki, the pizzeria offers elevated pies with distinctive bases made from a special dough ratio and fermented for two days. This results in exceptionally crisp and airy crusts that set it apart from traditional Neapolitan pizzerias in Tokyo.
TouristRestaurants.name: The Pizza Bar On 38th
TouristRestaurants.address: 2 Chome-1-1 Nihonbashimuromachi, Chuo City, Tokyo 103-8328, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Acclaimed Neapolitan-style pies, plus pasta & sides, in a steampunk setting with Beatles tunes.
TouristRestaurants.name: Seirinkan
TouristRestaurants.address: 2 Chome-6-4 Kamimeguro, Meguro City, Tokyo 153-0051, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Kanda Matsuya is a historic soba restaurant located in Tokyo's Kanda district, established in 1884 and housed in a beautifully preserved building from the Taisho era. The interior exudes a simple yet lively atmosphere, reminiscent of traditional sobaya. Despite its long history, Kanda Matsuya maintains an unpretentious and welcoming ambiance.
TouristRestaurants.name: Kanda Matsuya
TouristRestaurants.address: 1 Chome-13 Kanda Sudacho, Chiyoda City, Tokyo 101-0041, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: French-influenced tasting menus from a top-level Japanese chef, paired with wine or sake flights.
TouristRestaurants.name: L’Effervescence
TouristRestaurants.address: 2 Chome-26-4 Nishiazabu, Minato City, Tokyo 106-0031, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Yama is a French restaurant that specializes in assiette dessert, offering unique and mind-blowing dishes. Located in Shirokane since November 2022, the establishment has upgraded to a more luxurious atmosphere, showcasing an exquisite collection of antique glassware. The menu is updated every two months, featuring carefully selected seasonal fruits and ingredients sourced through meaningful relationships with farmers.
TouristRestaurants.name: Yama
TouristRestaurants.address: Japan, 〒108-0072 Tokyo, Minato City, Shirokane, 6 Chome−16−41, 1F

TouristRestaurants.description: Acclaimed, French-inspired tasting menus & drink pairings served at a counter around a show kitchen.
TouristRestaurants.name: Florilège
TouristRestaurants.address: 麻布台ヒルズ ガーデンプラザD 2F, 5 Chome-10-7 Toranomon, Minato City, Tokyo 105-0001, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Various cuts of meat, including Wagyu tongue, grilled tableside over charcoal in modern surrounds.
TouristRestaurants.name: Sumibi Yakiniku Nakahara
TouristRestaurants.address: Japan, 〒102-0085 Tokyo, Chiyoda City, Rokubancho, 4-3, ＧＥＭＳ市ヶ谷 ９F

TouristRestaurants.description: Fine-dining restaurant serving a seasonal & carefully sourced menu of innovative Japanese dishes.
TouristRestaurants.name: Narisawa
TouristRestaurants.address: 南青山ガーデンコート, 2 Chome-6-15 Minamiaoyama, Minato City, Tokyo 107-0062, Japan

TouristRestaurants.description: Udon Maruka is a popular noodle spot in Japan, known for its small kitchen and bar seating for about 12 diners. Despite the long queues, the restaurant operates efficiently, serving up deep umami aromas that keep fans coming back. The Sanuki/Kagawa-style udon is a standout feature, with perfectly chewy and satisfying noodles. Located in Jinbocho, this traditional Japanese eatery attracts office workers and students alike.
TouristRestaurants.name: Udon Maruka
TouristRestaurants.address: ニュー駿河台ビル 1F, 3 Chome-１６-1 Kanda Ogawamachi, Chiyoda City, Tokyo 101-0052, Japan
